00:01:27.340 --> 00:01:33.900
Now, today I want to continue.

00:01:33.900 --> 00:01:37.690
I didn't have time to finish
my discussion of the

00:01:37.690 --> 00:01:39.900
Fundamental Theorem
of Calculus 2.

00:01:39.900 --> 00:01:42.110
And anyway it's very important
to write it down on the board

00:01:42.110 --> 00:01:46.410
twice, because you want to
see it at least twice.

00:01:46.410 --> 00:01:48.370
And many more times as well.

00:01:48.370 --> 00:01:51.810
So let's just remind you, the
second version of the

00:01:51.810 --> 00:01:55.430
Fundamental Theorem of Calculus
says the following.

00:01:55.430 --> 00:02:01.470
It says that the derivative of
an integral gives you the

00:02:01.470 --> 00:02:03.630
function back again.

00:02:03.630 --> 00:02:08.310
So here's the theorem.

00:02:08.310 --> 00:02:13.160
And the way I'd like to use
it today, I started this

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:14.500
discussion last time.

00:02:14.500 --> 00:02:16.660
But we didn't get into it.

00:02:16.660 --> 00:02:20.120
And this is something that's on
your problem set along with

00:02:20.120 --> 00:02:23.190
several other examples.

00:02:23.190 --> 00:02:30.770
Is that we can use this to solve
differential equations.

00:02:30.770 --> 00:02:37.090
And in particular, for example,
we can solve the

00:02:37.090 --> 00:02:43.540
equation y' = 1 / x
with this formula.

00:02:43.540 --> 00:02:47.730
Namely, using an integral.

00:02:47.730 --> 00:02:54.770
L ( x ) is the integral
from 1 to x of dt / t.

00:02:54.770 --> 00:03:00.410
The function f ( t
) is just 1 / t.

00:03:00.410 --> 00:03:09.210
Now, that formula can be taken
to be the starting place for

00:03:09.210 --> 00:03:11.115
the derivation of all
the properties of

00:03:11.115 --> 00:03:12.510
the logarithm function.

00:03:12.510 --> 00:03:14.650
So what we're going to do right
now is we're going to

00:03:14.650 --> 00:03:28.190
take this to be the definition
of the logarithm.

00:03:28.190 --> 00:03:31.950
And if we do that, then I claim
that we can read off the

00:03:31.950 --> 00:03:34.510
properties of the logarithm
just about as easily as we

00:03:34.510 --> 00:03:36.150
could before.

00:03:36.150 --> 00:03:38.730
And so I'll illustrate
that now.

00:03:38.730 --> 00:03:42.340
And there are a few other
examples of this where

00:03:42.340 --> 00:03:45.450
somewhat more unfamiliar
functions come up.

00:03:45.450 --> 00:03:50.580
This one is one that in theory
we know something about.

00:03:50.580 --> 00:03:52.590
The first property of this
function is the one that's

00:03:52.590 --> 00:03:53.950
already given.

00:03:53.950 --> 00:03:59.580
Namely, its derivative
is 1 / x.

00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:01.830
And we get a lot of information
just out of the

00:04:01.830 --> 00:04:04.250
fact that its derivative
is 1 / x.

00:04:04.250 --> 00:04:06.440
The other thing that we need
in order to nail down the

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:09.815
function, besides its
derivative, is one value of

00:04:09.815 --> 00:04:10.280
the function.

00:04:10.280 --> 00:04:14.670
Because it's really not
specified by this equation,

00:04:14.670 --> 00:04:17.490
only specified up to a constant
by this equation.

00:04:17.490 --> 00:04:20.330
But we nail down that constant
when we evaluate it at this

00:04:20.330 --> 00:04:22.680
one place, L ( 1).

00:04:22.680 --> 00:04:25.360
And there we're getting the
integral from 1 to 1 of dt /

00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:28.430
t, which is 0.

00:04:28.430 --> 00:04:30.860
And that's the case with all
these definite integrals.

00:04:30.860 --> 00:04:33.000
If you evaluate them at their
starting places, the

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:34.460
value will be 0.

00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:37.430
And together these two
properties specify this

00:04:37.430 --> 00:04:42.800
function L (x), uniquely.

00:04:42.800 --> 00:04:46.800
Now, the next step is to try
to think about what its

00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:47.860
properties are.

00:04:47.860 --> 00:04:51.590
And the first approach to that,
and this is the approach

00:04:51.590 --> 00:04:54.706
that we always take, is to maybe
graph the function, to

00:04:54.706 --> 00:04:55.870
get a feeling for it.

00:04:55.870 --> 00:04:57.970
And so I'm going to take
the second derivative.

00:04:57.970 --> 00:05:00.860
Now, notice that when you have
a function which is given as

00:05:00.860 --> 00:05:02.790
an integral, its first
derivative is

00:05:02.790 --> 00:05:04.930
really easy to compute.

00:05:04.930 --> 00:05:06.670
And then its second derivative,
well, you have to

00:05:06.670 --> 00:05:08.290
differentiate whatever
you get.

00:05:08.290 --> 00:05:09.720
So it may or may not be easy.

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:12.880
But anyway, it's a lot harder in
the case when I start with

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:15.150
a function to get to the
second derivative.

00:05:15.150 --> 00:05:19.070
Here it's relatively easy.

00:05:19.070 --> 00:05:21.650
And these are the properties
that I'm going to use.

00:05:21.650 --> 00:05:26.410
I won't really use very much
more about it than that.

00:05:26.410 --> 00:05:29.660
And qualitatively, the
conclusions that we can draw

00:05:29.660 --> 00:05:33.040
from this are, first of all,
from this, for example we see

00:05:33.040 --> 00:05:38.970
that this thing is concave
down every place.

00:05:38.970 --> 00:05:41.640
And then to get started with the
graph, since I see I have

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:46.710
a value here, which is L( 1) =
0, I'm going to throw in the

00:05:46.710 --> 00:05:48.560
value of the slope.

00:05:48.560 --> 00:05:51.950
So L' ( 1), which I know is 1 of
1, that's reading off from

00:05:51.950 --> 00:05:55.180
this equation here,
so that's 1.

00:05:55.180 --> 00:05:59.200
And now I'm ready to sketch at
least a part of the curve.

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:07.680
So here's a sketch
of the graph.

00:06:07.680 --> 00:06:13.000
Here's the point (1, 0);
that is, x = 1, y = 0.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:17.420
And the tangent line,
I know, has slope 1.

00:06:17.420 --> 00:06:20.540
And the curve is concave down.

00:06:20.540 --> 00:06:27.530
So it's going to look
something like this.

00:06:27.530 --> 00:06:31.230
Incidentally, it's
also increasing.

00:06:31.230 --> 00:06:34.960
And that's an important
property, it's strictly

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:35.400
increasing.

00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:39.570
That's because L' (
x) is positive.

00:06:39.570 --> 00:06:43.560
And so, we can get from this
the following important

00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:44.220
definition.

00:06:44.220 --> 00:06:46.130
Which, again, is working
backwards from this

00:06:46.130 --> 00:06:46.610
definition.

00:06:46.610 --> 00:06:49.620
We can get to where we started
with a log in our previous

00:06:49.620 --> 00:06:50.620
discussion.

00:06:50.620 --> 00:06:58.100
Namely, if I take the level
here, which is y = 1, then

00:06:58.100 --> 00:06:59.730
that crosses the
axis someplace.

00:06:59.730 --> 00:07:04.180
And his point is what we're
going to define as e.

00:07:04.180 --> 00:07:13.140
So the definition of e is
that it's the value such

00:07:13.140 --> 00:07:20.220
that L ( e) = 1.

00:07:20.220 --> 00:07:22.800
And again, the fact that there's
exactly one such place

00:07:22.800 --> 00:07:25.810
just comes from the fact that
this L' is positive, so that L

00:07:25.810 --> 00:07:29.340
is increasing.

00:07:29.340 --> 00:07:33.530
No, there's just one other
feature of this graph that I'm

00:07:33.530 --> 00:07:35.930
going to emphasize to you.

00:07:35.930 --> 00:07:38.430
There's one other thing which
I'm not going to check, which

00:07:38.430 --> 00:07:40.060
you would ordinarily
do with graphs.

00:07:40.060 --> 00:07:41.950
Once it's increasing there are
no critical points, so the

00:07:41.950 --> 00:07:44.230
only other interesting
thing is the n's.

00:07:44.230 --> 00:07:46.540
And it turns out that the limit
as you go down to 0 is

00:07:46.540 --> 00:07:46.990
minus infinity.

00:07:46.990 --> 00:07:49.840
As you go over to the right
here it's plus infinity.

00:07:49.840 --> 00:07:53.340
It does get arbitrarily high;
it doesn't level off.

00:07:53.340 --> 00:07:55.820
But I'm not going to
discuss that here.

00:07:55.820 --> 00:07:58.400
Instead, I'm going to just
remark on one qualitative

00:07:58.400 --> 00:08:02.910
feature of the graph, which is
this remark that the part

00:08:02.910 --> 00:08:06.850
which is to the left
of 1 is below 0.

00:08:06.850 --> 00:08:17.350
So I just want to remark, why
is L (x) negative for x &lt; 1.

00:08:17.350 --> 00:08:19.190
Maybe I don't have room
for that, so I'll just

00:08:19.190 --> 00:08:23.550
put in here x &lt; 1.

00:08:23.550 --> 00:08:25.320
I want to give you
two reasons.

00:08:25.320 --> 00:08:27.980
Again, we're only working from
very first principles here.

00:08:27.980 --> 00:08:33.500
Just that the property that
L' = 1 / x, and L (1) = 0.

00:08:33.500 --> 00:08:39.390
So our first reason is that,
well, I just said it.

00:08:39.390 --> 00:08:41.430
L ( 1) = 0.

00:08:41.430 --> 00:08:46.910
And L is increasing.

00:08:46.910 --> 00:08:49.730
And if you read that backwards,
if it gets up to 0

00:08:49.730 --> 00:08:54.160
here, it must have been
negative before 0.

00:08:54.160 --> 00:08:57.960
So this is one way of seeing
that L ( x) is negative.

00:08:57.960 --> 00:09:00.150
There's a second way
of seeing it,

00:09:00.150 --> 00:09:02.410
which is equally important.

00:09:02.410 --> 00:09:07.470
And it has to do with just
manipulation of integrals.

00:09:07.470 --> 00:09:10.800
Here I'm going to start out
with L (x), and its

00:09:10.800 --> 00:09:11.430
definition.

00:09:11.430 --> 00:09:15.730
Which is the integral
from 1 to x dt / t.

00:09:15.730 --> 00:09:19.250
And now I'm going to reverse
the order of integration.

00:09:19.250 --> 00:09:21.500
This is the same, by our
definition of our properties

00:09:21.500 --> 00:09:24.200
of integrals, as the integral
from x to 1 with a

00:09:24.200 --> 00:09:30.010
minus sign dt / t.

00:09:30.010 --> 00:09:34.140
Now, I can tell that this
quantity is negative.

00:09:34.140 --> 00:09:39.690
And the reason that I can tell
is that this chunk of it here,

00:09:39.690 --> 00:09:44.010
this piece of it, is
a positive number.

00:09:44.010 --> 00:09:46.290
This part is positive.

00:09:46.290 --> 00:09:51.290
And this part is positive
because x &lt; 1.

00:09:51.290 --> 00:09:53.740
So the lower limit is less than
the upper limit, and so

00:09:53.740 --> 00:09:54.740
this is interpreted.

00:09:54.740 --> 00:09:58.070
The thing in the green box is
interpreted as an area.

00:09:58.070 --> 00:09:58.970
It's an area.

00:09:58.970 --> 00:10:03.120
And so negative a positive
quantity is negative, minus a

00:10:03.120 --> 00:10:08.280
positive quantity's negative.

00:10:08.280 --> 00:10:12.660
So both of these work
perfectly well as

00:10:12.660 --> 00:10:13.870
interpretations.

00:10:13.870 --> 00:10:16.010
And it's just to illustrate
what we can do.

00:10:16.010 --> 00:10:18.810
Now, there's one more
manipulation of integrals that

00:10:18.810 --> 00:10:23.380
gives us the fanciest
property of the ln.

00:10:23.380 --> 00:10:26.410
And that's the last one
that I'm going to do.

00:10:26.410 --> 00:10:29.450
And you have a similar thing
on your homework.

00:10:29.450 --> 00:10:32.920
So I'm going to prove that
this is, as I say, the

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:34.970
fanciest property of the log.

00:10:34.970 --> 00:10:39.680
On your homework, by the way,
you're going to check that L(

00:10:39.680 --> 00:10:46.680
1 / x) = - L ( x).

00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:52.070
But we'll do this one.

00:10:52.070 --> 00:10:54.780
The idea is just to plug
in the formula

00:10:54.780 --> 00:10:56.430
and see what it gives.

00:10:56.430 --> 00:11:02.830
On the left-hand side, I
have 1 to ab, dt / t.

00:11:02.830 --> 00:11:06.040
That's L ( ab).

00:11:06.040 --> 00:11:08.900
And then that's certainly equal
to the left-hand side.

00:11:08.900 --> 00:11:12.650
And then I'm going to now split
this into two pieces.

00:11:12.650 --> 00:11:14.600
Again, this is a property
of integrals.

00:11:14.600 --> 00:11:19.070
That if you have an integral
from one place to another, you

00:11:19.070 --> 00:11:20.620
can break it up into pieces.

00:11:20.620 --> 00:11:26.540
So I'm going to start at
1 but then go to a.

00:11:26.540 --> 00:11:33.950
And then I'm going to continue
from a to ab.

00:11:33.950 --> 00:11:36.580
So this is the question
that we have. We

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:38.010
haven't proved this.

00:11:38.010 --> 00:11:41.050
Well, this one is
actually true.

00:11:41.050 --> 00:11:42.880
If we want this to be
true, we know by

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:44.900
definition L ( ab) is this.

00:11:44.900 --> 00:11:48.460
We know, we can see it,
that L(a) is this.

00:11:48.460 --> 00:11:53.030
So the question that this boils
down to is, we want to

00:11:53.030 --> 00:11:54.960
know that these two
things are equal.

00:11:54.960 --> 00:12:01.320
We want to know that L ( b) is
that other integral there.

00:12:01.320 --> 00:12:04.960
So let's check it.

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:06.190
I'm going to rewrite
the integral.

00:12:06.190 --> 00:12:09.370
It's the integral from - sorry,
from lower limit a to

00:12:09.370 --> 00:12:13.940
upper limit ab of dt / t.

00:12:13.940 --> 00:12:17.370
And now, again, to illustrate
properties of integrals, the

00:12:17.370 --> 00:12:21.230
key property here that we're
going to have to use is change

00:12:21.230 --> 00:12:23.740
of variables.

00:12:23.740 --> 00:12:26.790
This is a kind of a scaled
integral where everything is

00:12:26.790 --> 00:12:29.990
multiplied by a factor of a from
what we want to get to

00:12:29.990 --> 00:12:32.010
this L ( b) quantity.

00:12:32.010 --> 00:12:38.240
And so this suggests that
we write down t = a u.

00:12:38.240 --> 00:12:40.460
That's going to be our trick.

00:12:40.460 --> 00:12:42.910
And if I use that new variable
u, then the change

00:12:42.910 --> 00:12:50.440
in t, dt, is adu.

00:12:50.440 --> 00:12:53.950
And as a result, I can write
this as equal to an integral

00:12:53.950 --> 00:12:58.010
from, let's see, dt = adu.

00:12:58.010 --> 00:13:00.080
And t = au.

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:05.740
So I've now substituted
in for the integrand.

00:13:05.740 --> 00:13:09.210
But on top of this, with
definite integrals, we also

00:13:09.210 --> 00:13:13.080
have to check the limits.

00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:17.140
And the limits work
out as follows.

00:13:17.140 --> 00:13:20.180
When t = a, that's
the lower limit.

00:13:20.180 --> 00:13:22.460
Let's just take a
look. t = a u.

00:13:22.460 --> 00:13:26.600
So that means that u
is equal to, what?

00:13:26.600 --> 00:13:28.710
It's 1.

00:13:28.710 --> 00:13:31.880
Because a * 1 = a.

00:13:31.880 --> 00:13:34.040
So if t = a, this is
if and only if.

00:13:34.040 --> 00:13:37.095
So this lower limit, which
really in disguise was where t

00:13:37.095 --> 00:13:45.400
= a, becomes where u = 1.

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:53.920
And similarly, when
t = ab, u = b.

00:13:53.920 --> 00:13:56.690
So the upper limit here is b.

00:13:56.690 --> 00:14:02.140
And now, if you notice, we're
just going to cancel these two

00:14:02.140 --> 00:14:02.920
factors here.

00:14:02.920 --> 00:14:07.280
And now we recognize that this
is just the same as the

00:14:07.280 --> 00:14:09.940
definition of L ( b).

00:14:09.940 --> 00:14:13.490
Because L ( x) is over
here in the box.

00:14:13.490 --> 00:14:16.270
And the fact that I use the
letter t there is irrelevant;

00:14:16.270 --> 00:14:18.020
it works equally well
with the letter u.

00:14:18.020 --> 00:14:22.430
So this is just L (b).

00:14:22.430 --> 00:14:33.160
Which is what we
wanted to show.

00:14:33.160 --> 00:14:35.680
So that's an example, and you
have one in your homework,

00:14:35.680 --> 00:14:45.380
which is a little similar.

00:14:45.380 --> 00:14:48.790
Now, the last example, that I'm
going to discuss of this

00:14:48.790 --> 00:14:51.390
type, I already mentioned
last time.

00:14:51.390 --> 00:14:54.430
Which is the function F ( x),
which is the integral from 0

00:14:54.430 --> 00:14:58.150
to x of e ^ -t^2 dt.

00:14:58.150 --> 00:15:04.130
This one is even more exotic
because unlike the logarithm

00:15:04.130 --> 00:15:06.030
it's a new function.

00:15:06.030 --> 00:15:10.230
It really is not any function
that you can express in terms

00:15:10.230 --> 00:15:13.870
of the functions that
we know already.

00:15:13.870 --> 00:15:18.750
And the approach, always, to
these new functions is to

00:15:18.750 --> 00:15:22.000
think of what their
properties are.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.570
And the way we think of
functions in order to

00:15:24.570 --> 00:15:26.570
understand them is to
maybe sketch them.

00:15:26.570 --> 00:15:27.960
And so I'm going to do
exactly the same

00:15:27.960 --> 00:15:29.830
thing I did over here.

00:15:29.830 --> 00:15:31.630
So, what is it that I
can get out of this?

00:15:31.630 --> 00:15:35.105
Well, immediately I can figure
out what the derivative is.

00:15:35.105 --> 00:15:38.000
I read it off from the
fundamental theorem.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.610
It's this.

00:15:41.610 --> 00:15:45.470
I also can figure out the value
at the starting place.

00:15:45.470 --> 00:15:48.440
In this case, the starting
place is 0.

00:15:48.440 --> 00:15:53.990
And the value is 0.

00:15:53.990 --> 00:15:57.600
And I should check the second
derivative, which is also not

00:15:57.600 --> 00:15:59.145
so difficult to compute.

00:15:59.145 --> 00:16:06.070
The second derivative
is - 2x e ^ x^2.

00:16:06.070 --> 00:16:10.650
And so now I can see that this
function is increasing,

00:16:10.650 --> 00:16:13.300
because this derivative is
positive, it's always

00:16:13.300 --> 00:16:14.670
increasing.

00:16:14.670 --> 00:16:17.940
And it's going to be concave
down when x is positive and

00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:20.540
concave up when x is negative.

00:16:20.540 --> 00:16:24.900
Because there's a minus sign
here, so the sign is negative.

00:16:24.900 --> 00:16:30.250
This is less than 0 when x is
positive and greater than 0

00:16:30.250 --> 00:16:36.800
when x is negative.

00:16:36.800 --> 00:16:40.160
And maybe to get started I'll
remind you F( 0), 0.

00:16:40.160 --> 00:16:45.220
It's also true that F' ( 0),
that just comes right out of

00:16:45.220 --> 00:16:52.450
this, F' ( 0) = e ^
- 0^2 which is 1.

00:16:52.450 --> 00:16:55.420
That means the tangent line
again has slope 1.

00:16:55.420 --> 00:16:57.090
We do this a lot
with functions.

00:16:57.090 --> 00:17:00.390
We normalize them so that their
slopes of their tangent

00:17:00.390 --> 00:17:03.600
lines are 1 at convenient
spots.

00:17:03.600 --> 00:17:06.390
So here's the tangent
line of slope 1.

00:17:06.390 --> 00:17:11.540
We know this thing is concave
down to the right and concave

00:17:11.540 --> 00:17:14.890
up to the left.

00:17:14.890 --> 00:17:17.570
And so it's going to look
something like this.

00:17:17.570 --> 00:17:20.860
With an inflection point.

00:17:20.860 --> 00:17:26.290
Right?

00:17:26.290 --> 00:17:32.530
Now, I want to say one more,
make one more remark about

00:17:32.530 --> 00:17:34.590
this function, or maybe two
more remarks about this

00:17:34.590 --> 00:17:36.050
function, before we go on.

00:17:36.050 --> 00:17:39.230
Really, you want to know this
graph as well as possible.

00:17:39.230 --> 00:17:42.220
And so there are just a
couple more features.

00:17:42.220 --> 00:17:45.825
And one is enormously helpful
because it cuts in half all of

00:17:45.825 --> 00:17:49.180
the work that you have. and
that is the property that

00:17:49.180 --> 00:17:51.800
turns out that this
function is i.

00:17:51.800 --> 00:17:56.860
Namely, F( - x) = - F(x).

00:17:56.860 --> 00:18:01.050
That's what's known as
an odd function.

00:18:01.050 --> 00:18:06.150
Now, the reason why it's
odd is that it's the

00:18:06.150 --> 00:18:08.500
antiderivative of something
that's even.

00:18:08.500 --> 00:18:10.430
This function in here is even.

00:18:10.430 --> 00:18:14.860
And we nailed it down so
that it was 0 at 0.

00:18:14.860 --> 00:18:17.540
Another way of interpreting
that, and let me show it to

00:18:17.540 --> 00:18:20.560
you underneath, is
the following.

00:18:20.560 --> 00:18:24.160
When we look at its derivative,
its derivative,

00:18:24.160 --> 00:18:28.190
course, is the function e ^ x.

00:18:28.190 --> 00:18:30.040
Sorry, e ^ - x ^2.

00:18:30.040 --> 00:18:37.430
So that's this shape here.

00:18:37.430 --> 00:18:41.670
And you can see the slope is 0,
but fairly close to 0, but

00:18:41.670 --> 00:18:42.610
positive along here.

00:18:42.610 --> 00:18:44.560
It's getting, this is
its steepest point.

00:18:44.560 --> 00:18:46.090
This is the highest
point here.

00:18:46.090 --> 00:18:48.210
And then it's leveling off
again; the slope is going

00:18:48.210 --> 00:18:50.670
down, always positive.

00:18:50.670 --> 00:18:56.860
This is the graph of
F' = e ^ -x^2.

00:18:56.860 --> 00:19:02.440
Now, the interpretation of the
function that's up above is

00:19:02.440 --> 00:19:08.510
that the value here is
the area from 0 to x.

00:19:08.510 --> 00:19:12.690
So this is area F(x).

00:19:12.690 --> 00:19:16.570
Maybe I'll color it in, decorate
it a little bit.

00:19:16.570 --> 00:19:25.120
So this area here is F ( x).

00:19:25.120 --> 00:19:28.840
Now, I want to show you
this odd property,

00:19:28.840 --> 00:19:30.900
by using this symmetry.

00:19:30.900 --> 00:19:35.350
The graph here is even, so in
other words, what's back here

00:19:35.350 --> 00:19:39.290
is exactly the same
as what's forward.

00:19:39.290 --> 00:19:42.580
But now there's a reversal.

00:19:42.580 --> 00:19:45.070
Because we're keeping track
of the area starting

00:19:45.070 --> 00:19:46.330
from 0 going forward.

00:19:46.330 --> 00:19:47.090
That's positive.

00:19:47.090 --> 00:19:49.940
If we go backwards, it's
counted negatively.

00:19:49.940 --> 00:19:52.790
So if we went backwards to - x,
we'd get exactly the same

00:19:52.790 --> 00:19:54.970
as that green patch
over there.

00:19:54.970 --> 00:19:56.810
We'd get a red patch
over here.

00:19:56.810 --> 00:20:01.280
But it would be counted
negatively.

00:20:01.280 --> 00:20:04.210
And that's the property
that it's odd.

00:20:04.210 --> 00:20:06.010
You can also check this
by properties

00:20:06.010 --> 00:20:08.920
of integrals directly.

00:20:08.920 --> 00:20:16.190
That would be just like
this process here.

00:20:16.190 --> 00:20:19.910
So it's completely analogous
to checking this

00:20:19.910 --> 00:20:25.410
formula over there.

00:20:25.410 --> 00:20:29.670
So that's one of the comments
I wanted to make about this.

00:20:29.670 --> 00:20:32.110
And why does this save us
a lot of time, if we

00:20:32.110 --> 00:20:33.100
know this is odd?

00:20:33.100 --> 00:20:36.270
Well, we know that the shape of
this branch is exactly the

00:20:36.270 --> 00:20:38.950
reverse, or the reflection,
if you like, of the

00:20:38.950 --> 00:20:39.940
shape of this one.

00:20:39.940 --> 00:20:42.180
What we want to do is flip it
under the axis and then

00:20:42.180 --> 00:20:44.960
reflect it over that way.

00:20:44.960 --> 00:20:53.590
And that's the symmetry property
of the graph of F(x).

00:20:53.590 --> 00:20:57.920
Now, the last property that I
want to mention is what's

00:20:57.920 --> 00:21:00.750
happening with the ends.

00:21:00.750 --> 00:21:03.570
And at the end there's
an asymptote,

00:21:03.570 --> 00:21:05.820
there's a limit here.

00:21:05.820 --> 00:21:10.700
So this is an asymptote.

00:21:10.700 --> 00:21:12.840
And the same thing down here,
which will be exactly because

00:21:12.840 --> 00:21:15.790
of the odd feature, this'll
be exactly negative.

00:21:15.790 --> 00:21:19.570
The opposite value over here.

00:21:19.570 --> 00:21:23.570
And you might ask yourself, what
